‌—ظVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2022-05-03-nushell_0_62.mdظ@022c5cb13b9fdf0bc6393d33cd88af17986234bf158abd4595bf0f8bd98b20a4³title: Nushell 0.62‘¬Nushell 0.62عگ



Nushell, or Nu for short, is a new shell that takes a modern, structured approach to your commandline. It works seamlessly with the data from your filesystem, operating system, and a growing number of file formats to make it easy to build powerful commandline pipelines.
Today, we're releasing version 0.62 of Nu. This release deeper integration with SQLite, new completion logic, and much more.
’گگعاTitle: title: Nushell 0.62
Path: Nushell 0.62
Content:




Nushell, or Nu for short, is a new shell that takes a modern, structured approach to your commandline. It works seamlessly with the data from your filesystem, operating system, and a growing number of file formats to make it easy to build powerful commandline pipelines.
Today, we're releasing version 0.62 of Nu. This release deeper integration with SQLite, new completion logic, and much more.
—ظVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2022-05-03-nushell_0_62.mdظ@ca9fc77ea2fbfde0013a4d25e1084e976c781d64430934976e66063a9e47bd64³title: Nushell 0.62‘¯Where to get itعsNu 0.62 is available as 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.62.0] pre-built binaries
 or from 
[link: https://crates.io/crates/nu] crates.io
. If you have Rust installed you can install it using 
``cargo install nu``
.
A note on this release:
 The binaries published by the Nu team now include a statically linked copy of the OpenSSL library (previously Nu used a shared library, AKA 'dynamic linking'). The goal of this change is to make Nu simpler to deploy with fewer dependencies.
This feature is enabled by the "static-link-openssl" Cargo feature, so it's easy to disable if needed when building Nu.
If you want all the built-in goodies, you can install 
``cargo install nu --features=extra``
.
As part of this release, we also publish a set of optional plugins you can install and use with Nu. To install, use 
``cargo install nu_plugin_<plugin name>``
.
’گگع­Title: title: Nushell 0.62
Path: Where to get it
Content:
Nu 0.62 is available as 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.62.0] pre-built binaries
 or from 
[link: https://crates.io/crates/nu] crates.io
. If you have Rust installed you can install it using 
``cargo install nu``
.
A note on this release:
 The binaries published by the Nu team now include a statically linked copy of the OpenSSL library (previously Nu used a shared library, AKA 'dynamic linking'). The goal of this change is to make Nu simpler to deploy with fewer dependencies.
This feature is enabled by the "static-link-openssl" Cargo feature, so it's easy to disable if needed when building Nu.
If you want all the built-in goodies, you can install 
``cargo install nu --features=extra``
.
As part of this release, we also publish a set of optional plugins you can install and use with Nu. To install, use 
``cargo install nu_plugin_<plugin name>``
.
—ظVarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2022-05-03-nushell_0_62.mdظ@eb4147eaa5021f78926aebbd42d31bfe5d5fc3f0eb6e83d4e162d842296e941f³title: Nushell 0.62‘ظ5Database connectivity (rgwood, elferherrera, fdncred)عڑA gap in the "Nushell story" up to this point has been that although Nushell is a language and shell focused on data, there wasn't yet any ability to query databases and work with their data. With 0.62, we take our first step in that direction.
New in this release is the 
``db``
 command, which allows you to connect to a SQLite database and create a SQL query to run on it:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
  > db open db.sqlite
    | db from table_a
    | db select a
    | db limit 10
    | db describe

```
With the 
``db open``
 command we open a connection to the database, then subsequent 
``db``
 commands build up a query step by step. One new twist with 
``db``
 for Nushell is that the query is built lazily, and will only be run once the data is needed.
Queries can also be written as raw SQL:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
  > db open db.sqlite | db query "SELECT a FROM table_a LIMIT 10"

```
And finally, the 
``open``
 command has been updated to be SQLite-aware:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
  > open db.sqlite

```
In all of the queries above, 
``db open db.sqlite``
 could be replaced by 
``open db.sqlite``
; 
``open``
 is able to detect databases by looking at file contents.
’گگعْTitle: title: Nushell 0.62
Path: Database connectivity (rgwood, elferherrera, fdncred)
Content:
A gap in the "Nushell story" up to this point has been that although Nushell is a language and shell focused on data, there wasn't yet any ability to query databases and work with their data. With 0.62, we take our first step in that direction.
New in this release is the 
``db``
 command, which allows you to connect to a SQLite database and create a SQL query to run on it:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
  > db open db.sqlite
    | db from table_a
    | db select a
    | db limit 10
    | db describe

```
With the 
``db open``
 command we open a connection to the database, then subsequent 
``db``
 commands build up a query step by step. One new twist with 
``db``
 for Nushell is that the query is built lazily, and will only be run once the data is needed.
Queries can also be written as raw SQL:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
  > db open db.sqlite | db query "SELECT a FROM table_a LIMIT 10"

```
And finally, the 
``open``
 command has been updated to be SQLite-aware:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
  > open db.sqlite

```
In all of the queries above, 
``db open db.sqlite``
 could be replaced by 
``open db.sqlite``
; 
``open``
 is able to detect databases by looking at file contents.
